    <string name="recommendation_text">Click the card for a new tip!</string>

    <string-array name="smart_tips">
        <item>Morning Feeding: Quails are most active in the morning. Ensure feed troughs are topped up by 7 AM.</item>
        <item>Water Check: Check water levels every 4 hours. Dehydration reduces egg production significantly.</item>
        <item>Lighting Tip: 14&#8211;16 hours of light per day is optimal for consistent egg laying.</item>
        <item>Airflow: Good ventilation is key to preventing ammonia buildup from droppings.</item>
        <item>Egg Collection: Collect eggs at least twice daily to prevent breakage or pecking behavior.</item>
        <item>Stress Management: Keep noise low around the cages. Sudden loud noises can stop quails from laying for days.</item>
        <item>Calcium Boost: Adding crushed oyster shells to feed helps strengthen eggshells.</item>
        <item>Molting: If quails stop laying and lose feathers, they may be molting. Provide extra protein during this time.</item>
        <item>Cage Cleaning: Clean waste trays daily to prevent ammonia odors.</item>
        <item>Bio-security: Wash your hands regularly before and after touching the quails or their eggs.</item>
        <item>Fresh Feed: Store feed in a cool, dry place to prevent mold growth.</item>
        <item>Temperature Control: Keep the quail house between 21°C and 32°C for optimal comfort and production.</item>
        <item>Humidity: Maintain relative humidity at 50-70% to keep quails healthy and eggs from drying out.</item>
        <item>Deworming: Consult a vet for a regular deworming schedule to ensure bird health.</item>
        <item>Predator Protection: Ensure cages are secure against rats, cats, and snakes.</item>
        <item>Record Keeping: Always track your daily egg counts to identify production trends early.</item>
        <item>Space: Ensure birds have enough space. Overcrowding leads to stress and cannibalism.</item>
        <item>Feed Quality: High-protein layer crumbles (around 20-22%) are best for laying quails.</item>
        <item>Dust Bathing: Provide a box of dry sand; quails love dust baths to stay clean and mite-free.</item>
        <item>Culling: Regularly identify and remove non-performing or sick birds to protect the flock.</item>
    </string-array>

